01:03:13,664 --> 01:03:15,289
It appears the word we couldn't make out

815
01:03:15,290 --> 01:03:18,134
had it's sound wave significantly
clipped by whoever made this tape.

816
01:03:18,739 --> 01:03:21,199
We restored it by amplifying specific frequencies

817
01:03:21,200 --> 01:03:22,200
seen on the oscilloscope.

818
01:03:23,684 --> 01:03:25,365
Cochinos is Spanish for pigs.

819
01:03:25,366 --> 01:03:26,366
Let me hear it again.

820
01:03:31,803 --> 01:03:32,981
<i>cochinos</i>

821
01:03:33,411 --> 01:03:37,163
And the siren noise we couldn't
pinpoint before were hiding church bells.

822
01:03:40,304 --> 01:03:43,536
For some reason other noises
were added to distort the bells.

823
01:03:43,537 --> 01:03:45,079
In the makeup table's mirror

824
01:03:45,080 --> 01:03:47,750
we can actually make out the
reflection of a church steeple

825
01:03:47,751 --> 01:03:51,104
whose three belfries correspond
with the bells you hear.

826
01:03:53,700 --> 01:03:56,295
The volume indicates that the church is across the street.

827
01:03:56,296 --> 01:03:58,191
Again, possibly on a town square.

828
01:03:59,135 --> 01:04:01,906
On the night stand, we can see a clock radio.

829
01:04:03,753 --> 01:04:05,756
It reads almost 10 o'clock

830
01:04:05,955 --> 01:04:07,789
which would correspond
with the church bells.

831
01:04:08,602 --> 01:04:10,659
I also have audio of the ceiling fan.

832
01:04:12,061 --> 01:04:15,045
It's a four blade standard ceiling
fan. We don't know where it's from.

833
01:04:16,497 --> 01:04:17,385
There is something here....

834
01:04:18,610 --> 01:04:19,943
could be nothing significant.

835
01:04:19,944 --> 01:04:21,889
Maybe a candle, a paper weight.

836
01:04:22,504 --> 01:04:25,775
Or it may be something personal that we
can identify the people in the room with.

837
01:04:26,627 --> 01:04:28,794
We are going to wash it
again. Maybe see what's there.

838
01:04:30,492 --> 01:04:31,864
How long till there some

839
01:04:33,229 --> 01:04:35,567
definition as to exactly where we are?

840
01:04:36,983 --> 01:04:38,366
We're going as quickly as we can sir.

841
01:04:49,118 --> 01:04:50,952
How are Clover and your little boy?

842
01:04:50,953 --> 01:04:52,976
Good. Thank you. You
know he is almost five.

843
01:04:54,288 --> 01:04:56,255
You may ????? for yourself in London.

844
01:04:57,615 --> 01:04:58,934
The World War is over.

845
01:04:59,179 --> 01:05:01,314
The war for the World has just begun

846
01:05:01,266 --> 01:05:02,400
and in every liberated country

847
01:05:02,401 --> 01:05:04,244
there will be a battle
between us and the Russians

848
01:05:04,335 --> 01:05:05,435
for their hearts and minds.

849
01:05:08,425 --> 01:05:09,624
Since we dropped the Bomb

850
01:05:09,625 --> 01:05:11,693
they're feeling a little
short between the legs.

851
01:05:11,719 --> 01:05:14,086
But the Russians still live in the nineteenth century.

852
01:05:14,287 --> 01:05:15,087
Beets and potatoes.

853
01:05:16,295 --> 01:05:17,773
All that will change dramatically.

854
01:05:17,774 --> 01:05:19,823
But right now, they're gobbling up territory

855
01:05:20,066 --> 01:05:21,922
taking home every
scientist they can steal.

856
01:05:22,433 --> 01:05:24,248
In ten years, they'll have a Bomb.

857
01:05:25,070 --> 01:05:28,169
We have to get anyone that can
be useful to us out of Berlin

858
01:05:28,446 --> 01:05:28,875
before they do.

859
01:05:34,522 --> 01:05:35,800
Churchill was right.

860
01:05:36,936 --> 01:05:39,311
We shouldn't have stopped
marching until we reached Moscow.

861
01:05:42,491 --> 01:05:44,216
They're from Switzerland.

862
01:05:44,217 --> 01:05:47,439
I had them sent, with a pouch, to Berlin.

863
01:05:48,024 --> 01:05:49,511
They're a weakness of mine.

864
01:05:49,512 --> 01:05:52,445
When I was a child, my mother would
always reward me with a chocolate.

865
01:05:55,797 --> 01:05:57,128
It's a dreadful habit.

866
01:05:57,672 --> 01:05:59,721
The chocolates or seeking approval?

867
01:06:01,152 --> 01:06:01,905
Both.

868
01:06:04,936 --> 01:06:07,698
He was an officer it the Abwehr,
German military intelligence.

869
01:06:10,850 --> 01:06:15,069
He says he knows the location of certain
Nazi V-2 rocket scientist in hiding.

870
01:06:15,268 --> 01:06:16,502
Ask him where he wants to go.

871
01:06:20,794 --> 01:06:23,117
He wants to go to Chicago.
He has relatives there.

872
01:06:23,823 --> 01:06:26,123
Tell him if he provides us
with the names and locations

873
01:06:26,165 --> 01:06:29,019
of the scientists I'll
arrange an exit visa for him.

874
01:06:29,866 --> 01:06:31,214
As soon as he serves his purpose,

875
01:06:31,254 --> 01:06:32,695
turn him over to the Nazi catchers.

876
01:06:44,002 --> 01:06:45,492
The next ????? is a group commander

877
01:06:45,561 --> 01:06:47,458
would like to speak with you about asylum.

878
01:06:53,206 --> 01:06:54,598
It's very ugly, isn't it?

879
01:06:54,763 --> 01:06:57,460
It isn't meant to be jewelry.

880
01:06:58,494 --> 01:07:01,259
I lost the sound in one ear, altogether.

881
01:07:01,525 --> 01:07:04,733
I can hear with the help of the apparatus

882
01:07:04,734 --> 01:07:06,877
out of this ear, but they
say in one year or so....

883
01:07:06,912 --> 01:07:08,435
You hardly notice it's there.

884
01:07:15,151 --> 01:07:17,830
The Russians are interested
in making a prisoner swap.

885
01:07:43,921 --> 01:07:48,416
We're prepare to offer you some
Jewish scientists liberated in the east

886
01:07:48,417 --> 01:07:51,657
for some Nazi scientists
living here in Berlin.

887
01:08:00,472 --> 01:08:02,883
These are the names
we're willing to discuss.

888
01:08:38,578 --> 01:08:41,881
I understand your
cryptonym for me is Ulysses.

889
01:08:43,296 --> 01:08:46,621
Isn't that from the James
Joyce book or the Greek myth.

890
01:08:52,862 --> 01:08:55,311
Do you what our code name is for you?

891
01:09:00,217 --> 01:09:01,279
Mother.

892
01:09:05,002 --> 01:09:08,710
A took the first hot bath
yesterday I've taken in three years.

893
01:09:09,409 --> 01:09:11,420
Since the siege of Stalingrad.

894
01:09:13,540 --> 01:09:15,337
I sat for hours...

895
01:09:16,315 --> 01:09:18,500
looking out the window,

896
01:09:19,540 --> 01:09:20,851
soaking.

897
01:09:34,334 --> 01:09:35,817
When I was a soldier

898
01:09:35,818 --> 01:09:37,575
my fingers we're frost bitten.

899
01:09:39,272 --> 01:09:41,143
Since then, when I get cold

900
01:09:41,949 --> 01:09:43,646
there is a pain.

901
01:09:47,176 --> 01:09:48,855
Maybe you shouldn't live in Russia.

902
01:09:51,222 --> 01:09:53,160
We all have our weaknesses.

903
01:09:55,518 --> 01:09:56,787
What is yours?

904
01:09:59,945 --> 01:10:02,153
I had heard you were silent.

905
01:10:03,984 --> 01:10:05,551
Made of stone, they said.

906
01:10:07,197 --> 01:10:08,785
What is the expression?

907
01:10:10,481 --> 01:10:12,174
The silence is deafening.

908
01:10:16,221 --> 01:10:18,360
You're going to be a formidable

909
01:10:19,315 --> 01:10:20,922
adversary, Mother.

910
01:10:30,320 --> 01:10:32,709
I look forward to our association.

911
01:10:34,977 --> 01:10:37,397
I hope it lasts for a long time.

912
01:10:53,397 --> 01:10:54,800
I love you.

913
01:10:55,848 --> 01:10:58,811
People who really love each
other don't have secrets.

914
01:10:59,877 --> 01:11:01,763
You are safe here with me.

915
01:11:01,764 --> 01:11:03,631
We were able to make
out the brand of the fan.

916
01:11:03,632 --> 01:11:06,406
It's called a ?????. It's Belgian.

917
01:11:07,234 --> 01:11:08,767
The object on the night stand

918
01:11:09,374 --> 01:11:11,354
we're still trying to find out what this is.

919
01:11:12,656 --> 01:11:14,429
We just can't get any
more definition out of it.

920
01:11:20,524 --> 01:11:21,398
Who is this?

921
01:11:23,185 --> 01:11:24,435
Who is this?

922
01:11:26,157 --> 01:11:27,123
Hello father.

923
01:11:27,445 --> 01:11:29,180
You have a birthday coming up.

924
01:11:29,501 --> 01:11:31,006
I'm going to be five soon.

925
01:11:31,812 --> 01:11:33,709
Well you're a big boy.

926
01:11:34,493 --> 01:11:36,931
?????

927
01:11:41,502 --> 01:11:42,726
Is your mother there?

928
01:11:42,727 --> 01:11:44,576
What? I can't hear you.

929
01:11:47,279 --> 01:11:48,487
Is your mother there?

930
01:11:49,364 --> 01:11:51,454
She's getting dressed
to go out with her friend.

931
01:11:51,455 --> 01:11:52,829
He has a new car.

932
01:11:53,142 --> 01:11:54,335
He lets me drive with him.

933
01:11:57,475 --> 01:11:59,168
Hello Mr. Wilson, this is Edna.

934
01:11:59,169 --> 01:12:00,745
Mrs. Wilson is upstairs.

935
01:12:00,947 --> 01:12:02,004
She's getting ready for dinner.

936
01:12:02,415 --> 01:12:03,919
I'll tell her you are on the phone.

937
01:12:06,743 --> 01:12:07,831
I'll call back.

938
01:12:12,948 --> 01:12:13,973
<i>door knocking</i>

939
01:12:15,788 --> 01:12:16,863
Pardon me.

940
01:12:18,512 --> 01:12:20,076
Do you need me for anything else?

941
01:12:20,514 --> 01:12:21,913
No. Thank you.

942
01:12:22,671 --> 01:12:23,188
Guten Nacht.

943
01:12:23,488 --> 01:12:24,499
Guten Nacht.

944
01:12:30,854 --> 01:12:32,742
Do you ever eat Mr. Wilson.

945
01:12:33,810 --> 01:12:34,744
I like to cook.

946
01:12:35,879 --> 01:12:37,222
Would you like a home cooked meal?

947
01:12:46,038 --> 01:12:49,149
Have you ever read Ovid's
Metamorphosis in the original Latin?

948
01:12:50,657 --> 01:12:51,600
It's quite beautiful.

949
01:12:55,651 --> 01:12:57,512
I grabbed the pile of dust

950
01:12:57,513 --> 01:12:58,513
and holding it up

951
01:12:59,821 --> 01:13:02,740
foolishly ask for as many
birthdays as the grains of dust.

952
01:13:03,831 --> 01:13:06,582
I forgot to ask that they be years of youth.

953
01:13:08,508 --> 01:13:09,043
Bravo

954
01:13:22,846 --> 01:13:24,270
I should be going.

955
01:13:32,796 --> 01:13:34,398
Would you like to stay?

956
01:13:37,941 --> 01:13:39,014
Would you like me to.

957
01:13:40,966 --> 01:13:42,357
I would like you to very much.

958
01:13:52,635 --> 01:13:54,225
Maybe we can go somewhere together?

959
01:13:55,340 --> 01:13:57,178
The lakes in Bavaria are so beautiful.

960
01:13:58,636 --> 01:14:00,897
There was an inn there before the war.

961
01:14:00,898 --> 01:14:02,774
where they served
breakfast in bed all day.

962
01:14:27,264 --> 01:14:28,264
Yena ?????

963
01:14:31,516 --> 01:14:33,003
I hope you never go home.

964
01:14:36,457 --> 01:14:38,152
Bavaria is a really beautiful place.

965
01:14:40,338 --> 01:14:41,558
I was born there.

966
01:14:41,559 --> 01:14:42,731
My grandmother

967
01:14:43,633 --> 01:14:44,519
lived there.

968
01:14:45,688 --> 01:14:46,860
I really miss her.

969
01:14:49,160 --> 01:14:50,191
Why don't we go.

970
01:15:05,670 --> 01:15:08,050
I let a stranger into our house.

971
01:15:10,029 --> 01:15:11,695
<i>door knocking</i>

972
01:15:15,618 --> 01:15:16,606
Dies da?

973
01:15:18,020 --> 01:15:18,738
Danka.

974
01:16:18,437 --> 01:16:21,001
Mother. Father is here.

975
01:16:21,553 --> 01:16:22,361
Mother.

976
01:16:29,160 --> 01:16:30,331
Hello Edward.

977
01:16:32,065 --> 01:16:32,976
Hello Clover.

978
01:16:36,931 --> 01:16:37,887
I ah.

979
01:16:40,387 --> 01:16:41,928
I like to be called Margaret now.

980
01:16:46,098 --> 01:16:47,455
It's very nice to see you.

981
01:16:49,852 --> 01:16:51,192
It's good to see you too.

982
01:16:54,709 --> 01:16:56,100
I made something or you.

983
01:17:00,977 --> 01:17:01,768
You see?

984
01:17:02,300 --> 01:17:03,171
It's a ship.

985
01:17:05,013 --> 01:17:05,754
But it's got

986
01:17:06,393 --> 01:17:07,664
the flag of England.

987
01:17:09,598 --> 01:17:11,721
And then I put a pirate flag there.

988
01:17:13,120 --> 01:17:13,711
And if you like

989
01:17:13,712 --> 01:17:15,268
you can count

990
01:17:15,754 --> 01:17:17,411
how many sails are there.

991
01:17:18,486 --> 01:17:19,592
You want to try that?

992
01:17:25,857 --> 01:17:27,028
Fifteen.

993
01:17:27,264 --> 01:17:28,088
That’s right.

994
01:17:29,234 --> 01:17:30,137
Fifteen.

995
01:17:32,128 --> 01:17:33,334
No. No. It's yours.

996
01:17:33,774 --> 01:17:34,556
I made it for you.

997
01:17:50,441 --> 01:17:51,730
If it's alright with you I thought

998
01:17:52,761 --> 01:17:54,943
maybe we could sleep in
separate beds for a while.

999
01:17:54,944 --> 01:17:57,046
Just until we can get
to know each other again.

1000
01:17:59,196 --> 01:18:00,718
I made up the spare room.

1001
01:18:02,792 --> 01:18:03,510
All right.

1002
01:18:12,465 --> 01:18:14,068
What do you hear from your brother John.

1003
01:18:18,348 --> 01:18:20,358
I thought you knew he was killed in Burma.

1004
01:18:20,658 --> 01:18:21,659
In 1944.

1005
01:18:23,952 --> 01:18:25,750
You never mentioned it
in any of your letters.

1006
01:18:29,177 --> 01:18:30,718
There wasn't very much to say.

1007
01:18:39,702 --> 01:18:41,444
Six year is a long time.

1008
01:18:45,361 --> 01:18:46,678
I was lonely.

1009
01:18:46,679 --> 01:18:48,647
And I was with a man, once.

1010
01:18:51,731 --> 01:18:53,384
He wasn't very interesting.

1011
01:18:57,640 --> 01:18:59,212
Were you with anyone?

1012
01:19:02,444 --> 01:19:03,828
It was a mistake.

1013
01:19:20,925 --> 01:19:23,752
Thank you for the
ship you made.  For me.

1014
01:19:27,068 --> 01:19:28,080
Your welcome.

1015
01:19:29,453 --> 01:19:30,756
I'm glad you like it.

1016
01:19:32,881 --> 01:19:34,992
Mother said you were at the war.

1017
01:19:35,563 --> 01:19:38,614
Did you fight? Did you kill anybody?

1018
01:19:42,320 --> 01:19:43,104
No.

1019
01:19:47,186 --> 01:19:48,072
Good night.

1020
01:19:49,079 --> 01:19:49,798
Good night.

1021
01:20:10,159 --> 01:20:12,542
Hello Father. Hello Edward. Hello

1022
01:20:13,968 --> 01:20:14,705
Hello dear.

1023
01:20:14,706 --> 01:20:16,356
There is somebody waiting
for you in the den.

1024
01:20:18,957 --> 01:20:19,710
General!

1025
01:20:22,325 --> 01:20:23,276
Edward.

1026
01:20:25,483 --> 01:20:27,105
I'm sorry to barge in on you like this.

1027
01:20:27,106 --> 01:20:28,668
You wife kindly helped me to a drink.

1028
01:20:30,865 --> 01:20:31,623
My feet!

1029
01:20:31,624 --> 01:20:33,162
I keep cutting off pieces of them.

1030
01:20:33,992 --> 01:20:36,270
It's not dignified for a man
to have to die from the feet up.

1031
01:20:43,042 --> 01:20:46,291
Well, while everybody has been
feeling good about themselves

1032
01:20:46,292 --> 01:20:49,594
the Soviets, without firing a shot
have taken over half the World.

1033
01:20:50,043 --> 01:20:51,400
They're breathing down our necks.

1034
01:20:51,689 --> 01:20:53,389
They'll be in our back
yard before you know it.

1035
01:20:53,884 --> 01:20:55,031
So I've been telling the President

1036
01:20:55,196 --> 01:20:57,764
about our need to create a
foreign intelligence service

1037
01:20:57,765 --> 01:21:00,264
one that will do in peace time what
it was asked to do during the war.

1038
01:21:01,455 --> 01:21:03,446
Phillip Allen will be heading the agency

1039
01:21:03,447 --> 01:21:04,822
Richard Hayes will be his exec

1040
01:21:04,857 --> 01:21:06,595
and you'll be taking division C.

1041
01:21:06,596 --> 01:21:09,241
Special operations that
report only to the director.

1042
01:21:10,026 --> 01:21:11,767
It will be limited to overseas, obviously.

1043
01:21:11,768 --> 01:21:13,536
Subversive operations,

1044
01:21:13,537 --> 01:21:15,359
intelligence gathering and analysis.

1045
01:21:16,117 --> 01:21:18,660
And I'd be interested in
your thoughts about this.

1046
01:21:20,078 --> 01:21:23,660
Particularly, in your area of
expertise. Counter intelligence.

1047
01:21:23,773 --> 01:21:25,882
I'd be glad to help in any way I can.

1048
01:21:26,489 --> 01:21:27,127
That's all right.

1049
01:21:27,322 --> 01:21:29,481
Edward. Go outside.

1050
01:21:30,826 --> 01:21:31,857
Excuse me sir.

1051
01:21:32,045 --> 01:21:33,005
Margaret.

1052
01:21:42,466 --> 01:21:43,602
Thank you.

1053
01:21:52,840 --> 01:21:56,953
I have to tell you, I have some
real problems with this whole thing.

1054
01:21:56,954 --> 01:21:57,954
Despite how much we need it.

1055
01:21:59,598 --> 01:22:02,709
I'm concerned that too much power
will end up in the hands of too few.

1056
01:22:03,288 --> 01:22:06,894
It's always in someone's best interest
to promote enemies, real or imagined.

1057
01:22:07,202 --> 01:22:09,447
I see this as America's eyes and ears.

1058
01:22:09,448 --> 01:22:11,932
I don't want it to become
it's heart and soul.

1059
01:22:13,832 --> 01:22:15,816
So I told the President,
for this to work

1060
01:22:15,817 --> 01:22:18,560
they’re going to have to be some
kind of civilian oversight.

1061
01:22:18,889 --> 01:22:19,901
Oversight?

1062
01:22:21,576 --> 01:22:23,624
How can you have a covert organization

1063
01:22:23,625 --> 01:22:25,129
if you have people
looking over your shoulder?

1064
01:22:25,130 --> 01:22:27,045
You know who gave Hitler his power?

1065
01:22:27,219 --> 01:22:28,757
The clerks and the book keepers.

1066
01:22:29,653 --> 01:22:30,802
The civil servants.

1067
01:22:31,936 --> 01:22:33,742
I have this one weakness.

1068
01:22:34,685 --> 01:22:35,852
I believe in a just God.

1069
01:22:37,250 --> 01:22:39,624
I always seem to err on
the side of democracy.

1070
01:22:46,551 --> 01:22:48,807
This must be a nice
place to raise a family.

1071
01:22:50,119 --> 01:22:51,040
I never had the time.

1072
01:22:52,625 --> 01:22:53,952
I'll be dead in less than a year.

1073
01:22:57,215 --> 01:22:58,566
I love this country.

1074
01:22:59,208 --> 01:23:01,862
We all do sir. We all do.

1075
01:23:11,877 --> 01:23:13,472
No matter what anyone tells you,

1076
01:23:13,526 --> 01:23:14,960
there'll be no one you can really trust.

